{
  "text": "[24, [CITATION_1] Fibrin glue has been used as an alternative to sutures for securing the conjunctival grafts.One study has reported recurrence rate of 5.3% for glue versus 13.5% for sutures and suggested that immediate adherence of the graft and lack of postoperative inflammation may inhibit fibroblast ingrowth and reduce the recurrence.The main issue in using commercial fibrin glue, despite viral inactivation techniques, is the transmission of infectious agents such as parvovirus B19 (HPV B19). Furthermore, anaphylactic reaction has been reported after the use of (TISSEEL) fibrin sealant which was due to bovine protein aprotinin.Foroutanet al.",
  "citation_candidates": [
